===Etymology===
From {{bor|en|it|fascismo}}, from {{m|it|fascio||[[fasces]], [[bundle]], [[group]]}} + {{m|it|-ismo||[[-ism]]}} with direct reference to {{w|Benito Mussolini}}'s ''{{w|fasci di combattimento}}'' ("[[fight]] [[club]]s"), from {{der|en|la|fasces}}, bundles of axes and rods carried before the magistrates of the ancient [[Roman Republic]] as representative of their power of life and death. Originally with exclusive reference to {{w|Fascist Italy}} which used the fasces as an emblem, later broadened to describe all of the {{w|Axis Powers}} of {{w|World War II}}, and subsequently used as a general term of opprobrium in English and international political discourse.

